{
  "extends": "./tsconfig.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    // ESM emit (PR #203 R4 â€” fixes architect-reviewer Critical):
    //   The ESM build must be importable by Node-native ESM consumers
    //   (i.e., `import('@lfmt/shared-types')` from a Node 22 process,
    //   not just via a bundler). Node-native ESM does NOT probe file
    //   extensions, so the previous combination of `module: ESNext` +
    //   `moduleResolution: node` emitted bare `from './jobs'` imports
    //   that failed at runtime with ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND.
    //
    //   Why `module: ESNext` + `moduleResolution: bundler` (vs the
    //   apparently-canonical `node16` + `node16`):
    //     - `node16` decides ESM-vs-CJS per source file by walking up
    //       to the nearest enclosing `package.json` and reading its
    //       `type` field. The parent `shared-types/package.json`
    //       deliberately has no top-level `"type"` (the package's
    //       primary identity stays CJS for backend Lambda compat),
    //       so `node16` would conclude every `.ts` file in `src/` is
    //       CJS and silently emit CJS into `dist/esm/`. Pre-creating
    //       `dist/esm/package.json` does NOT help because the walk-up
    //       starts from each SOURCE file, not the output file.
    //     - `module: ESNext` forces real ESM emit unconditionally,
    //       sidestepping the package.json walk-up entirely.
    //     - `moduleResolution: bundler` (TS 5.x+) is the matching
    //       resolver: it preserves explicit `.js` extensions verbatim
    //       in the output and accepts ESM emit. `bundler` does NOT
    //       enforce `.js` extensions in the SOURCE the way `node16`
    //       would â€” that drift guard lives in the dual-package
    //       contract test (`src/__tests__/dual-package.test.ts`),
    //       which spawns a Node-native `import()` against
    //       `dist/esm/index.js` and fails with ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND
    //       if anyone removes a `.js` extension from a relative
    //       import. Test-as-contract is sufficient and avoids the
    //       config gymnastics of forcing `node16` to lie about the
    //       parent package.json type.
    //
    //   The base `tsconfig.json` (CJS build) under `module: commonjs`
    //   happily accepts the same `.js`-suffixed imports, stripping
    //   them as needed â€” so the source compiles cleanly under both
    //   targets without divergence.
    "module": "ESNext",
    "moduleResolution": "bundler",
    "outDir": "./dist/esm",
    "declaration": true,
    "declarationMap": true
  }
}
